    <h2>6. Complete File Architecture & Technical Analysis</h2>
    <p>This section provides a comprehensive breakdown of every critical file across our three separated workspaces, analyzing their individual purposes and justifying their structures from the perspectives of <strong>Security</strong>, <strong>Speed</strong>, and <strong>Best Practices</strong>.</p>

    <h3>6.1 Standalone Backend Server (<code>autoverse-server/</code>)</h3>
    <p>
        The dedicated backend server isolates core API routing, data ingestion, vector RAG math, and Groq inference tasks.
    </p>

    <h4>6.1.1 Root Configuration Files</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><code>package.json</code>: Manages node-specific server dependencies. Keeps our runtime server separated from building/bundling packages (Security).</li>
        <li><code>tsconfig.json</code>: Rigid CommonJS and Node typing configurations. Enforcing static typing eliminates runtime bugs and enables the V8 runtime engine to perform optimizations (Speed).</li>
        <li><code>tsup.config.ts</code>: Bundles the entire server workspace into a single lightweight production file (<code>dist/server.js</code>), accelerating cold-starts and reducing server footprint (Speed).</li>
        <li><code>.env</code>: Securely persists database, Groq, and server port configuration variables away from version control (Security).</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>6.1.2 Orchestrator & Server Source Files (<code>/src</code>)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><code>index.ts</code>: Server launchpad and entry point. Loads environmental states and mounts active listeners securely (Best Practice).</li>
        <li><code>server.ts</code>: Express configuration exposing CORS-enabled routes, API routes, and history endpoints. Strict CORS settings filter out unauthorized cross-origin requests immediately (Security).</li>
        <li><code>autoverse.ts</code>: Central orchestration instance coordinate. Manages system configurations, intent classifier workflows, and active RAG prompts without leaking variables to global scopes (Security).</li>
        <li><code>widget.ts</code>: Servers a dynamic, host-configured widget build on-the-fly, allowing client sites to embed using a simple static script tag.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>6.1.3 AI Agent Core & Algorithms (<code>/src/agent</code> & <code>/src/recommender</code>)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><code>intentClassifier.ts</code>: Syntactically routes users' questions without triggering high-latency LLM calls for standard tasks, reducing response latency to milliseconds (Speed).</li>
        <li><code>planner.ts</code>: Breaks down multi-layered requests into incremental execution blocks, protecting models from token-buffer limits (Speed).</li>
        <li><code>action.ts</code> & <code>actionExecutor.ts</code>: Converts chatbot intents into highly rigid JSON execution instructions rather than executing raw SQL/JS, mitigating any prompt injection risks (Security).</li>
        <li><code>ranking.ts</code> (Recommender): Provides lightweight cosine-similarity calculations and relevancy weighting to output product recommendations in milliseconds (Speed).</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>6.1.4 Data Ingestion & Scrapers (<code>/src/ingestion</code>)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><code>crawler.ts</code>: Crawls target domains asynchronously with concurrency caps, protecting the target site from Denial of Service (DoS) behaviors (Best Practice).</li>
        <li><code>extractor.ts</code>: Uses Cheerio to parse HTML fast without spinning up memory-heavy chromium browsers, and sanitizes scraped text blocks to avoid cross-site scripting (Speed & Security).</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>6.1.5 Retrieval Core & Stores (<code>/src/core</code>, <code>/src/store</code>, <code>/src/types</code>)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><code>rag.ts</code>: Feeds models with semantic context from target domains, eliminating hallucinations and ensuring private host information remains isolated (Security).</li>
        <li><code>groq.ts</code>: Groq interface enabling 500+ token/sec inference speeds using LPU architectures (Speed).</li>
        <li><code>cache.ts</code>: In-memory key-value caching intercepts repetitive support questions without consuming LLM APIs, preventing Denial of Wallet (DoW) vectors (Speed & Security).</li>
        <li><code>vectorStore.ts</code> & <code>embeddings.ts</code>: High-speed mathematical calculations for vector comparison.</li>
        <li><code>botStore.ts</code> & <code>historyStore.ts</code>: Centralizes file storage operations. Writing chat histories separately prevents write-locks on read-heavy appearance configuration maps (Best Practice).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>6.2 Highly Optimized NPM Package (<code>autoverse-fyp/</code>)</h3>
    <p>
        The lightweight widget library published to NPM. It has been completely stripped of all server-side dependencies and files, creating a zero-dependency, ultra-light build.
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><code>package.json</code>: Declares **zero production dependencies**, resulting in a tiny npm bundle footprint and zero installation overhead (Speed).</li>
        <li><code>tsup.config.ts</code>: Utilizes <code>tsup</code> to build two target assets: an index package (<code>dist/index.js</code>) for ESM/CJS developer builds, and a browser bundle (<code>dist/browser.mjs</code>) for single-tag web injection.</li>
        <li><code>tsconfig.json</code>: Strict ES2020 browser and DOM compiler configurations.</li>
        <li><code>src/widget.ts</code>: Pure, vanilla client bubble generator with zero external imports. Encapsulates interactive support views, custom Micro-animations, dynamic styles, and local session stores.</li>
        <li><code>src/browser.ts</code>: Side-effect browser installer that auto-mounts widgets only in document-ready states, eliminating React render blocks or server-side rendering (SSR) crashes (Best Practice).</li>
        <li><code>src/index.ts</code>: Public package module boundary, exporting strictly client-facing widget controllers (Best Practice).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>6.2 Frontend Dashboard (<code>dashboard/</code>)</h3>

    <h4>6.2.1 Root Configuration Files</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><code>vite.config.ts</code>: Configures the Vite bundler. Vite leverages native ES modules during development for instant Hot Module Replacement (HMR) and uses highly optimized Rollup for production builds, resulting in lightning-fast loading of the dashboard (Speed).</li>
        <li><code>package.json</code> & <code>tsconfig.json</code>: Maintains dependency integrity and strict typing for the React application.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>6.2.2 Core App Files (<code>/src</code>)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><code>main.tsx</code>: The React DOM entry point. Uses React 18's Concurrent Mode (`createRoot`) to keep the UI responsive even during heavy state updates (Speed).</li>
        <li><code>App.tsx</code>: Defines the routing structure. It enables client-side routing so the browser doesn't need to reload the page when navigating between settings and bot lists, providing a native app-like experience (Speed).</li>
        <li><code>index.css</code>: Vanilla CSS with custom properties (variables). Bypassing heavy CSS frameworks ensures the smallest possible payload and fastest browser render times (Speed).</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>6.2.3 API Integration (<code>/src/api</code>)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><code>client.ts</code>: Centralized Axios instance. It handles all backend communication, ensuring that authorization headers (if added) and error handling are uniformly applied to every single request, preventing secure routes from being accidentally hit without credentials (Security).</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>6.2.4 User Interface Components (<code>/src/components</code>, <code>/src/pages</code>)</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><code>BotHistory.tsx</code>: Renders the chat logs. It isolates the rendering logic, ensuring that viewing massive chat histories doesn't cause the rest of the application to lag (Speed).</li>
        <li><code>CodeSnippet.tsx</code>: Displays the embed code to the user. It explicitly sanitizes the output to ensure no malicious scripts can be injected into the admin's clipboard (Security).</li>
        <li><code>WidgetPreview.tsx</code>: Renders a live visual preview of the bot based on user settings. The component securely parses user-inputted hex codes and CSS values, preventing CSS injection attacks within the dashboard (Security).</li>
        <li><code>BotList.tsx</code>, <code>BotSettings.tsx</code>, <code>CreateBot.tsx</code>: The main views. These forms utilize controlled React components, meaning input is strictly validated in memory before it is ever sent to the server, providing the first line of defense against malformed data (Security).</li>
    </ul>

